The Wikipedia article for Scillus links this river to the Selinountas, however this link is erroneous. Where Wikipedia links the Selinountas is far northeast of where Xenophon describes this river. Additionally, it is worth noting that in this passage Xenophon is talking about how coincidental it is that there are multiple rivers named Selinus.
This river is one in Ephesus, and not the same Selinus Xenophon mentions earlier in this section.

Likely refers to Corylas I, ruler of Paphlagonia from c. 425-400 BCE. He is mentioned in a Wikipedia article listing the rulers of Paphlagonia, but himself does not have an article.

This seems to refer to the Chaldians from the famous Chalybes/Chaldia conundrum in Book 4, rather than the Chaldeans or a similar ethnic group Mesopotamia, as they are listed in conjunction and order with the Taochians and Carduchians. Also, the translation uses the ethnonym "Chaldaeans",¬† not "Chaldeans" (though also not "Chaldians," which nowadays seems to be more popular).
